{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471663"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"382"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/382"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.1,0.07,0.06,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45355"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/382"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"370"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18205"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45355"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy is brought into the Emergency Department at 2:00am by his mother. She reports that he has been unwell with a \u0027cold\u0027 over the last four days. He then woke with a distressing barking, brassy cough. He has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications, and is up to date with all vaccinations. On examination, he appears distressed. There is audible stridor which resolves as he settles. At rest, his respiratory rate is 24/min, he is not using accessory muscles to breathe, and his SpO2 is 96% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral dexamethasone","Humidified oxygen","Nebulised salbutamol","Nebulised adrenaline","Oral azithromycin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has mild croup, as he has no stridor at rest, no increase in respiratory rate, no increased work of breathing, and is alert with normal oxygen saturation. He can be managed with a single dose of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E 0.15 mg/kg and discharged home once symptom-free. Dexamethasone is used in hospitals due to availability and is the ideal choice of steroid. Prednisolone 1 mg/kg is an alternative that is often required for 2-3 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHumidified oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is only given if the child is hypoxic, which is a late sign in croup and would automatically classify the child as having severe life-threatening croup requiring immediate treatment with nebulised adrenaline and senior clinician/ICU review, in addition to systemic corticosteroids. Other signs of moderate-to-severe croup include stridor that persists at rest, increased work of breathing, distress/agitation or drowsiness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E can be given for moderate-to-severe asthma, which classically presents in a child \u003E12 months with cough, wheeze +/- increased work of breathing, often precipitated by a viral respiratory tract infection. Delivery of salbutamol via metered dose inhaler with a spacer has been shown to be just as efficacious in managing acute asthma as nebulised salbutamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is usually given in specific cases of significant stridor and work of breathing, whilst awaiting the effect of steroids. It should only be given under the direction of senior clinicians.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment given for pertussis, which classically presents in a child that has been unwell for a week with cough and coryza, and subsequently develops paroxysms of a hacking cough followed by a high-pitched \u0022whoop\u0022 sound as the child inhales to quickly fill their empty lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Signs of moderate-to-severe croup include stridor that persists at rest, increased work of breathing, distress/agitation or drowsiness."],"references":["Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis). In: Royal Children\u2019s Hospital clinical practice guidelines [online]. 2017. Available at:  https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Croup_Laryngotracheobronchitis/","Majumdar S, Bateman NJ, Bull PD Paediatric stridor Arch Dis Child. 2006;91:ep101-ep105. Available at: https://ep.bmj.com/content/91/4/ep101","Fitzgerald D, Mellis C, Johnson M, Allen H, Cooper P, Van Asperen P. Nebulized budesonide is as effective as nebulized adrenaline in moderately severe croup. Pediatrics. 1996 May;97(5):722-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8628614/#:~:text=Conclusion%3A%20This%20study%20does%20not,patients%20with%20moderately%20severe%20croup.","Cates CJ, Welsh EJ, Rowe BH. Holding chambers (spacers) versus nebulisers for beta-agonist treatment of acute asthma. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2013;2013(9):CD000052. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7032675/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"382"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T20:46:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-13T20:47:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"382"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45355"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/370"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Laryngotracheobronchitis","synonyms":["Croup"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:05+09:30","updatedA